When we discuss human productivity, we should start with the understanding all humans are productive about 5/8 of their lifetime.  Generally, we all do our time as useless dependents . . . and part of the basis for human society is that we invest in the sheer number of human beings we can produce. Mark Twain, having swung a pickaxe in the sun for a living, and having edited a newspaper, said he'd gladly edit the paper for free, in order to avoid swinging the pickaxe in the sun for money. We each have senses, and a mind that can attempt (at least) to take in information from our environment, sorting, sifting, collating, mixing, matching, etc.  But that mind can also reach out to the world that sends the signals, acting, reacting, moving, shaping, building, destroying. I think there is a pretty big conflation about masculinity and femininity that seems to be going on here, at least with David Fuller, Louise Mazanti, and Rafia Morgan, which is that they are implying a strong association between masculinity and aggression. I think that aggression is far too general of a term to link to either masculinity or femininity. Think about it... if a woman is mad at someone, maybe a friend, or her husband, would it at all be weird for her to yell at them? Men complain about women nagging them all the time. But yelling is surely an aggressive thing to do. Likewise, men keeping their cool is often seen as masculine. I think aggressiveness or lack thereof is just universal: it's a strategy that men or women will use to suit their needs. A woman might try to smooth talk you into something, sure, but so could a man. Likewise, a man or woman could yell at you to try to get what they want.   So we need something much more specific than aggressiveness when it comes to assessing this issue. I would actually argue that Cathy Newman was being pretty feminine. She was simply being aggressive and feminine. After all, people aren't saying Peterson was acting feminine in that same interview, even though he was less aggressive, right? So even in that very interview featured throughout this whole video, we seem to have the conflation I'm talking about in action. I say Newman was being feminine because she is trying to use victimhood to win her arguments, and then frame Peterson as a perpetrator. That's feminine. And she could do it gently or aggressively, but as long as she is pursuing this goal, this is a feminine behavior. If a woman is mad about something, she may well use aggression to resolve what is happening. It's less about the tone of the person and more about, their strategic goals -- is the person trying to play victim to win the argument, or are they letting the logic of the argument speak for itself?  Another aspect of being feminine is avoiding risk, particularly, social risk. Newman's aggressive tactics are not generally risky for a woman to do, because she knows that society is typically on the side of the woman who is playing victim, so they will typically declare her the winner of that kind of debate, or at least, not shame her for simply being aggressive towards a man. Maybe this interview was an exception, but generally it is not socially risky for a woman to be aggressive towards a man, because society is protecting her and supporting her in such situations. I think she would be acting in a masculine way if her viewpoint was not socially acceptable, but she was aggressively expressing it anyway (but again, she could try the gentle approach as well; as long as the viewpoint she is expressing is risky to express, she is being masculine by taking that risk).   So I think that it's not really about aggression versus passivity, and that those approaches are just means that the person wants to use to achieve their goals, or means that they personally prefer or identify with. What the goals are, are closer to the mark in defining masculinity or femininity. I am not intending to make what I mentioned here an exhaustive account of the masculine and feminine. Not at all: I think there are several other things that go into masculinity and femininity that I didn't mention here. (For example, I think that masculinity and femininity both value competition, but what separates them is that masculinity values competition for the sake of competition (for example, sports, video games, where often all that a person wins from them is bragging rights). Maybe that's what people mean by "combative," but it's often pretty moot because women are just as competitive as men if they are trying to get something that will benefit them.)  I was just offering an example, that goes in line with my point that aggression and passivity is pretty universal between the genders.  Both men and women can decide if they should be intimidating, or charming, two classic strategies that both know of very well. Sometimes I wonder if people will think that if a wife is yelling at her husband that it doesn't count as aggression simply because she is a woman. No, aggression is aggression. Some feminine traits are better than others depending on the situation, and I do think that there are some feminine traits that would be beneficial to see in journalism that we are not typically seeing, but it has nothing to do with being more or less aggressive.

I suppose as an older person, younger people might see us as stoic. But that's not really what it is. My wife is tougher than me--even with a disability. She doesn't let it stop her, and she focuses on what makes her happy. We don't see ourselves as stoic. We see these younger people on the left as behaving like they're butthurt over every little thing! They only make us look stoic by comparison. We don't hide our feelings--but we're old enough to know it's about more than what you're feeling at the moment. Feelings can be fleeting. It's also about commitment to what you want for your life and your family's lives. It's about setting goals.  We didn't have time for entitlement and being butthurt--it wouldn't have gotten us anywhere. Guess what? Nobody cares if you're butthurt! We had a family to raise and support. And we loved them and wanted to do that. Peterson is right--it's about accepting responsibility. But once you do and move forward, life is very fulfilling and even fun! It makes you feel good about yourself. I'm proud of our kids, too. They are not weinie-whiners. They're well-adjusted and happy. They're intelligent and successful, and a joy to be around. Our kids laughed at the absurdity of some of these butthurt kids in college. They didn't need a "safe space." Those spaces aren't for the bold who know what they want. There is some truth to the meme of "first world problems", after all.  One thing the young on the left need to do is chill a little, and live and let live. Stop trying to make everyone think and behave the way you do, and hating them when they don't. It's a waste of time. It'll only hold you back. Just learn to accept people and do what you need to do to move yourself forward. And for Pete's sake, create a plan for your life. Think about where you want to be and how to get there. Peterson's advice to "clean your room" is the advice a good father would give his kids. It's the beginning of taking responsibility for yourself, and kids should have learned that before they started school. A lot of these "kids" in their 20's and 30's should have learned that a long time ago. Until they do, they'll be stuck in a rut and waste their lives. They'll be a burden to the people around them.  I sometimes wonder how these "kids" will behave when they're my age.

I'd like to offer a bit of nuance here regarding the "personal responsibility" ethos. After a tour in Iraq I began exploring leftist ideology because I realized that while personal responsibility is a great ethos to live by, it's not necessarily a great ethos in which to govern men and nations. There are technological, economic, and cultural forces at play that affect the individual, communities, and even the nation as a whole--but have nothing to do with the individual's actions. While you can easily make a case that it is the individual's responsibility to adapt to these changes, there are instances where governmental intervention can reduce some of that burden and disruption in the life of the individual. Should the government work to alleviate the suffering of its people? That's up for debate. I think the political left (not to be confused with the social left) hopes conservatives begin to see the need to take personal responsibility for things the left perceives as societal threats, things like over-consumption, climate change, a bloating health insurance industry, corrupted campaign finance incentives, egregious prescription drug price gouging, and predatory corporatism. Many of these cases run counter to the neoconservative pro-business, pro-economic growth ideology, so the right remains blind to these flaws in the system. Personally, I'm sympathetic to the over-consumption narrative after having fought in a war for natural resources. That makes sense to me at a visceral level.  In the absence of this change in perception from the right, I fear the only recourse for people concerned about these particular social issues will be massive governmental legislation. Should a society tell the senior citizen to pull themselves up by the bootstraps after a pharmaceutical drug company increases a prescription drug price by 1,300% in order to fulfill its fiduciary responsibility to maximize profits for its share holders? Or is it the individual's responsibility to enter into government and take on the pharmaceutical lobby and install legislation to bar that type of corporate behavior in the future? Or build a fortune so they can create their own benevolent pharmaceutical empire?  Should a society ignore predictable outcomes and hold the individual responsible to change their entire livelihood and even where they live as a result of climate change (a force which is out of their personal control)? Staring at that hard realization, an act of feverish activism to push forward something like the Green New Deal is an act of personal responsibility for that individual.  I'm also sensitive to Dr. Peterson's influence on American politics when he lives in a country with socialized medicine. People in the United States, working full time and contributing to society, are having to file bankruptcy for medical bills at an alarming rate. Filing bankruptcy hinders their potential to participate in economic life. These people are engaged in a political battle Dr. Peterson is naive to and may have a hard time empathizing with.   I'm not trolling. I'm simply offering up a different perspective for this intellectual crowd to chew on.

Ive been feeling this for a while. Glad to see someone put it into film. I've thought a lot about this, and while i agree that we need to have open dialogue between both sides, there is an aspect to this that i cannot reconcile. i have trouble with some of the thoughts that peterson justifies. Often they are thoughts/ideas that are dying relics of a more conservative or religious past version of our culture. A few off the top of my head being 'there is a large percentage of the population that cannot contribute to society' + 'the mental stability of any woman the age of thirty not expressing an extreme desire for kids should be questioned' + His general comments on Marx/philosophers which misrepresent their writing to argue in favor of his ideology.  Its these aspects to his position that make me uncomfortable for a few reasons. One, he often speaks in over generalizations, often to excite a base into agreement, often against an argument that doesnt really exist or misrepresents the other side. Two, the insistence that by pointing out faults with society he is somehow providing solutions, even though its often defeatist in that it only once again excites his base with no real productive dialogue. And lastly, he is often pandering to a base that is often pushing dying ideologies. for example, the ideas that IQ and race are somehow relevant to a modern competitive society. More clearly, that somehow skirting the line of obviously dysfunctional race relations is in any way healthy, with the blanket counter argument that 'well since its not PC i must be on a higher intellectual ground because im braver than you'.   Now im not blind. I know the left is equally guilty of this. But i think in order to have functional dialogue in the first place, we need to redraw the lines of rational dialogue. What are facts, and what are opinions? What is productive and what is defeatists? What is biased cultural assumptions, and what is reality? These distinctions no longer exists. And yes i mean on both sides. Its for this fact that I am truly skeptical of our cultures ability to have real dialogue. You see this in our modern debates. They are simply saying things that their base agrees with, with some strange illusion that if their side yells the loudest in affirmation to them then they must have won...?   In conclusion, i think for me, the most disappointing aspect to all of this is that there are truly things that we all agree on. Everyone deserves freedom, everyone deserves compensation for hard work, and everyone (i hope) agrees that money should not be involved in politics. But heres the thing. We arent having that dialogue. Even this video isnt really even hinting at it. We are all collectively distracted by separatists political ideologies ( the core of this debate). Instead of having real dialogue, we are arguing about gender, race, and sex, when in reality these are fundamentally non-issues. These are historically mechanisms that those in power use to separate those without. So...unfortunately im a pessimist in this regard, and i have very little hope of our ability to see our way out of this intellectual/cultural mess. Only because, apparently, as far as i can tell, we have yet to ever officially get out of it as it is just as alive today as it was 100 years ago.  Anyways, i hope this reaches some reasonable people out there.

Sergiu Popovici interesting perspective on the nature of morality. On that particular point, I would have to agree to an extent. I would agree that morality (typically with judeo/Christian roots) confers a certain fitness benefit that would drive evolution in terms of implementing a strong familial structure and creating a society were interpersonal interactions are relatively predictable (I know with relative confidence that I will not likely be killed without provocation and most people will predict that I will not kill them based on common morality in most modern societies).  Why do we have on average 2-3 children if we can pump out 8? Because you cannot nurture 8 children to become as fit individuals as a well-nurtured 2 in today's society where technology ensures a higher likelihood of survival, thus negating the previous necessity to have many children.   Morality is subjective, but still widely universal. I agree that things we consider to be moral typically confer some sort of fitness benefit to the individual (even altruism in social animals confers fitness to the individual, even if it comes at an initial cost). We have a drive, like all animals, to reproduce and not only survive but thrive. Doing good in the world increases the fitness and chance of survival for our offspring. But we do not want to create a social society with equal outcome but rather one with equal opportunity. In a society with equal opportunity, the best get rewarded. In a way, a perfect meritocracy has darwinistic principles in which the highest quality offspring succeed and the lowest quality perish. Ironically, such social Darwinism is considered immoral even though it confers an evolutionary advantage...so there must be another component to the evolution/morality argument.

Sergiu Popovici morality confers an implicit benefit to survival though, even if at a cost to the individual survival. Look at social creatures such as ants, monkeys, vampire bats, etc. All of these species exhibit altrusism, a benefit to the group at a cost to the individual. A vampire bat will regurgitate blood to feed an individual that has failed to feed and is starving. Monkeys will screech to alert the group that a predator is nearby at a cost of making it's presence known to the predator. From a darwinistic perspective, this is puzzling. Imagine that some members of a group of monkeys give alarm calls but others do not.  By selfishly refusing to give an alarm call, the monkeys that remain silent have an advantage while benefiting from others. So we should expect natural selection to favor monkeys that do not give alarm calls over those that do. If that is the case, how did the behavior evolve in the first place and why does it persist?  The same can be said for human morality and our current social structures. Take communism/socialism for example. In the context of human nature or Darwinism, it is a total failure of an idea. Imagine if every monkey let out an alarm call instead of just one, the chance of survival of the group is no different, but the cost is shared among the group which should be good. The problem is that it is easily subverted. What if one monkey decides not to make itself known, now its chances of survival are exponentially higher than any one member of the group. To keep that from happening, you need an enforcer to maintain group behavior which is why communist regimes fail miserably.  In most Western societies, we exhibit altruism, but not equally between individuals. The result is a non-perfect but overall high fitness environment where the group, in general is successfully able to survive.   Interestingly, biologists describe monkeys who remain silent as "selfish" and those who give the alarm call as "altruistic". Selfishness is seen as being immoral and being altruistic is typically seen as "good." Maybe we think we ought to be good, even though we benefit from being selfish. Maybe teaching "goodness" is itself selfish, because we know we confer a benefit from the goodness of others. Group selection is more powerful than individual selection in social creatures, thus these "values" persist and will probably not go away. They existed thousands of years ago and exist today.

Truly, we're listening to discourse that has not been spoken in modern institutions. We need a collective reminder of the wisdom of the ancients, which we would have otherwise gained from the Catholic Church had we not scoffed it so much.

Peterson presents a simplistic argument of 'no blank slate' to support the notion of clear-cut binary gender distinctions.  Well, yes, blank slate outlook has been discredited, read Pinker's excellent and accessible book on the topic.  However, individuals are not a Bell curve.  Bell curves represent populations.  To pick the tips of the Bell curves and call them 'Woman' and 'Man' is to horribly misrepresent the science of gender and behaviour.  It also ignore the correlation and causation problem.  As for the categories of 'male' and 'female', biologists cannot agree on the must-have attributes for these, hence the issue of Caster Semenya, along with many other problems for sex and gender, including hermaphroditism, intersex, XXY and other variants.  Of course, Bell curves are useful, but Peterson offers his particularly biased valuation of their use as 'fact'.  His framing of 'women' ignores the significant variation within that Bell curve, and its overlap with the attributes held by 'men'.  Indeed, his position is merely conservative-thinking, nothing original about it.  Conservative attitudes have historically dominated our lives, legislated against gay sex, against female suffrage, against married women having rights to property etc. etc.  In many places, conservative thinking still holds people back, and yet Peterson's issue is with calling a very small number of people by a gendered pronoun of their choosing, rather than one chosen by the appearance of their genitalia at birth.  This seems extremely petulant.  Perhaps he has been eating too much broccoli and chicken, and not taking enough SSRIs, because this 'new' Peterson has a touch of irrational mania about him, not to mention a few Bannon-style dollars.

My view has always been that authority and responsibility are inseparable. You can't give someone authority if they don't also take responsibility for the outcome, and you can't have someone be responsible for something if they don't have the authority to effect it. This is equally true for responsibility for yourself; if you don't have authority over yourself and your life then you can't be expected to be responsible for your life's outcome. When I realized that this is what libertarian philosophy advocates for I adopted it. You should be free to do whatever you want with your life and your body, but remember that you are also responsible for the outcome of your decisions. The world and everyone else in it doesn't owe you or me anything, and forcing them to pretend otherwise will only lead to unhappiness and dissatisfaction for everyone. This is not an argument against kindness and charity when they are warranted, because they are not forced pretenses; they come naturally, are sincere, and are a part of your personal authority. I also think that the occasional hardship of personal authority and responsibility encourages empathy and compassion.

In the most ancient societies, order was created by choosing scapegoats and initiating violence against them.       The mechanism became very sophisticated and smart people knew how to gain power through out it.       For instance when a city was struck by plague, a traveller, who had seen the course of the plague in other cities, knew how to choose the time when the plague had killed off most of the week people and it would begin to recede in severity.   He would claim that he could find the evil spirit causing the plague and dispose of it.   He would pick out some crazy, ugly, dirty, disreputable person and convince the city to stone him to death.   When the plague receded as he knew it would, the whole city was grateful and rewarded the outsider with wealth and power.       Rulers specialized in selecting people to blame for one problem or another and resolving problems by scapegoating.        Jesus put an end to the process as people learned to identify with the scapegoat and question the whole process.   But it was possible to twist the process, and that is what we see now.   People elbow one another aside vying for the position of victim and scapegoat,  and they attempt to make a scapegoat out of the straw man of a victimizer.   Now men are claiming victim (scapegoat) status.         It becomes a world full of crying victims, debating about who is the most victimized, so they can victimize someone else.       The deep problem is the failure to make a distinction between scapegoat violence and righteous violence.   Violent suppression of the guilty is not the same as violence against the innocent.        We are too damned prissy about punishing criminals who claim to be scapegoats, that is, members of an oppressed class, and we give them too many unearned and undeserved rewards.  We are also too savage about punishing members of a perceived privileged class, mainly white males.         It is social justice gone mad, neurotic, and destructive of all order and lawfulness.   The law needs to be blindfolded again, making no distinction between any classification of people.   Perhaps it is possible to describe a crime as a person doing a thing to x, y, and z persons without reference to sex, race, religion, or social position,  and to determine guilt and punishment anonymously, by juries who don't even see one another.

gytfunke This. People are different, and some women will choose career as the thing that individually makes them most happy. For that matter, most men will choose career as the central domain of their life, but some will choose family and children instead.  That's fine, and to be expected if the big 5 traits Peterson talks about apply to those kinds of life choices, and there's no reason to thimk they aren't part of the engine behind that difference. The thing about, say, the agreeableness difference between women and men is that the distributions really are different, but also overlapping. That means the 30% of most disagreeable women are more hard-nosed and blunt (and perhaps also ambitious) than the most agreeable (and perhaps homebody-ish) 30% of men. I wouldn't be surprised if this is the case for all the other differences Peterson talks about; there might not be much difference in personality between the most orderly progressive and the most open conservative.   This is why capitalism and classical liberalism both predicate on individual choice and work well because of that; because individuals even within a gender or political orientation will be much more different than intuition would suggest, and differences between groups the opposite. Hence no social role applies categorically (sexual orientation as role, for example). That doesn't mean the aggregate differences don't exist, as the Left tries to make it seem like, they certainly do exist. But they aren't categorical. Because of this the two systems allow for people to specialize to their own individual talents and propensities, because most people are an edge case in something or another, and liberal capitalism unlocks that potential that more rigid roles based on innate category (which is low-resolution compared to looking at each individual separately) forsakes.   Edit: A good analogy is handedness. The rule "People are more skillful with their right hand" is true. But not categorically (can confirm as a lefty). Some conservatives like surprises, some progressives crave routine. Some women are loud and contrarian by nature. Some men are soft-spoken and gentle. It's simply that the opposite preference is much more common, and that fact should be (but isn't) acknowledged in our current society despite it being able to explain differences in outcome between groups.

I haven't read Jung, just ordered some books such as Modern Man In Search Of A Soul which sounds complementary to Nietzsche proclaiming the death of God (loss of faith because of morality, the cultivation of truthfulness, along with the philosophizing inherited from the ancient Greeks, leading to science). Which is why I would recommend Alex Kierkegaard, quote: 241. There's always a single concept to be found at the bottom of every philosopher's philosophy. With Heraclitus it's flux, with Schopenhauer will, with Stirner the ego, with Kierkegaard faith, with Nietzsche power, while with Baudrillard it's seduction and with me immersion. But what is the quest for power if not the way in which the immersed ego maximizes its influence in the flux by having faith in itself while following its seduced will? And I could easily add Plato's forms, Spinoza's Nature, Hegel's spirit, and all the rest. Hell, even Wittgenstein's silence (via way, perhaps, of Shakespeare) will have a place in my elaboration of the¬†ultimate form of thinking¬†by the time I am done. My masterstroke will be the inclusion of even all the abortive half-concepts and pseudo-concepts floating around in the swamp of the subhuman brain ‚Äî they too will have a place in the grand scheme of things (though as befits the ideas of small, tiny creatures, theirs will naturally be a very small, very tiny place) ‚Äî and all the rest, beyond that point, will be silence. 813. Once more on Leibniz vs. Newton. Leibniz's God is supremely rational, but Newton's is the common Christian God whose will is "unknowable", and that's why on all the deepest issues Newton has nothing to say, but simply attributes them all to "God" ‚Äî i.e. to his own ignorance. Lichtenberg: "Are all our conceptions of God, after all, anything more than personified incomprehensibility?" So, for Lichtenberg, God is a catch-all term for everything one doesn't understand. So the more one comes to understand, the smaller this sphere becomes ‚Äî and therefore this God ‚Äî while at the same time the ego grows at the exact same rate, and begins to demand "its own" (Stirner). Finally, right past the tipping point, where the amount of one's insight surpasses the amount of one's ignorance, calling the ignorance "God" ceases to make much sense, and using it for the insight instead ‚Äî i.e. for the ego, for oneself ‚Äî is the only logical thing to do. And that's how the God concept shifts from designating "personified incomprehensibility" to personified comprehensibility, and God transforms from a "holy" ghost and spirit... to flesh and blood (and metal, and circuits): to an "evil" man and superman; to me and my descendants.
